        <!-- Presentation Guide -->
        <div class="presentation-guide">
            <h2>🎤 Presentation Guide</h2>
            <p><strong>When You Share (3-5 minutes):</strong></p>
            <ol>
                <li><strong>Briefly summarize your week's topic</strong> - One sentence about the main idea</li>
                <li><strong>Answer your four questions</strong> - Share what you learned from the Bible</li>
                <li><strong>Share your supporting verses</strong> - Read them from your Bible and explain briefly how they connect</li>
                <li><strong>Optional:</strong> Share one personal application - How will this affect your life?</li>
            </ol>

            <div class="example-format">
                <strong>Example Format (using Week 1):</strong><br><br>
                "My week was on 'Are You Really A Christian?' by Paul Washer. The main idea is that true Christianity involves a complete transformation, not just going to church or saying a prayer once.<br><br>
                For question 1, the Bible teaches that God's grace not only saves us (justification) but also gives us power to become holy (sanctification). It's not just forgiveness—it's transformation.<br><br>
                For question 2, I learned from 2 Corinthians 5:17 that being a 'new creation' means we have new desires, new affections, and a new heart that longs for holiness instead of sin.<br><br>
                For question 3, James 4:4 teaches that friendship with the world is hostility toward God. We can't love God and love the world's values at the same time.<br><br>
                For question 4, Scripture shows that if God is truly working in us, we'll see evidence: growing desire for holiness, conviction over sin, and progressive transformation—not perfection, but direction.<br><br>
                My supporting verses were 2 Corinthians 5:17 which says 'Therefore, if anyone is in Christ, the new creation has come: The old has gone, the new is here!' and Philippians 1:6 which says 'He who began a good work in you will carry it on to completion.' These verses show that salvation includes transformation.<br><br>
                One way I want to apply this is to regularly examine my life and ask: Is there evidence that God is making me holy? Am I more like Christ than I was last year?"
            </div>

            <div style="margin-top: 15px; padding: 10px; background: white; border-radius: 5px;">
                <strong>Remember:</strong>
                <ul>
                    <li>The study guide helps you understand, but quote from the Bible itself</li>
                    <li>Goal is to practice studying God's Word independently</li>
                    <li>We're learning together about the gospel</li>
                    <li>No pressure to be perfect - we're all growing!</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div style="text-align: center; margin-top: 30px; padding: 20px; background: #f8f9fa; border-radius: 10px;">
            <p style="font-size: 14px; color: #666;">
                <strong>Access study guides at:</strong><br>
